It's inspired by a mix of punk rock,

13
00:00:47,695 --> 00:00:49,395
Riot Grrl, and bouncy physics.

14
00:00:49,555 --> 00:00:51,956
So try to create as much chaos as possible

15
00:00:51,996 --> 00:00:52,736
and have fun with that.

16
00:00:53,696 --> 00:00:58,038
I also helped make this game called Stellar Smooch with AP Thompson who also helped me

17
00:00:58,058 --> 00:01:01,979
a lot with this talk so make sure to go follow them on Twitter at Bad Tenders.

18
00:01:03,079 --> 00:01:08,521
Stellar Smooch is a game about kissing and loneliness and it got into the IGF in 2014.

19
00:01:09,362 --> 00:01:13,363
We also made a cool alt control version which we showed at the Wild Rumpus that year as

20
00:01:13,403 --> 00:01:13,683
well.

21
00:01:13,963 --> 00:01:19,325
You and a friend have to simultaneously squeeze this big red yoga ball at the correct time

22
00:01:19,585 --> 00:01:21,646
to get the space probes to collide with each other.

23
00:01:23,245 --> 00:01:25,627
The year after, AP and I teamed up again,

24
00:01:25,747 --> 00:01:27,409
and we went on to create BeGlitched.

25
00:01:28,009 --> 00:01:30,051
BeGlitched is a game about insecurity

26
00:01:30,231 --> 00:01:32,353
in our computers and ourselves.

27
00:01:32,873 --> 00:01:35,135
And though it may look cute and silly,

28
00:01:35,535 --> 00:01:38,117
it's actually much more difficult than it seems.

29
00:01:38,658 --> 00:01:39,979
It's currently out on Steam

30
00:01:40,379 --> 00:01:42,160
and about to get an iOS release.

31
00:01:42,341 --> 00:01:44,002
So if you're interested in checking it out,

32
00:01:44,122 --> 00:01:45,763
definitely go buy it and give us our money.

33
00:01:48,171 --> 00:01:50,212
So while I was working on BeGlitched,

34
00:01:50,352 --> 00:01:53,093
I also took this prototyping class taught by Bennett Foddy

35
00:01:53,453 --> 00:01:56,615
where I made a game a week based on a specific prompt.

36
00:01:56,995 --> 00:01:58,495
So here are some of the prototypes

37
00:01:58,535 --> 00:01:59,836
that came out of that class.

38
00:02:00,336 --> 00:02:02,537
The theme for this one was 10 seconds.

39
00:02:02,837 --> 00:02:04,678
So Morning Makeup Madness is a game

40
00:02:04,738 --> 00:02:07,179
where you have 10 seconds to do your makeup.

41
00:02:07,939 --> 00:02:11,361
It's a personal game and it's drawn from my own experience

42
00:02:11,441 --> 00:02:12,581
of waking up super late

43
00:02:12,661 --> 00:02:14,462
and not having enough time to get ready.

44
00:02:15,518 --> 00:02:18,181
Wobble Yoga is another prototype I made in that class.

45
00:02:18,942 --> 00:02:20,604
The theme for this one was shape shift.

46
00:02:20,724 --> 00:02:22,086
It was actually a Ludum Dare theme.

47
00:02:22,626 --> 00:02:24,509
And I decided to make this QWOP-like game

48
00:02:24,769 --> 00:02:27,552
where you have to contort this noodly-limbed avatar

49
00:02:27,633 --> 00:02:30,336
through this series of really challenging yoga poses.

50
00:02:30,756 --> 00:02:32,038
And this game is also based

51
00:02:32,338 --> 00:02:34,301
off of my own personal experience.

52
00:02:36,779 --> 00:02:39,582
So anyway, I'm currently working on a personal game

53
00:02:39,762 --> 00:02:41,604
about dieting called Consume Me,

54
00:02:42,244 --> 00:02:45,027
and it's focused on this specific time period in my life

55
00:02:45,407 --> 00:02:47,149
where I just wasn't super happy

56
00:02:47,229 --> 00:02:49,231
with the way I looked and with my body.

57
00:02:50,031 --> 00:02:51,993
Even though the subject matter is quite dark,

58
00:02:52,274 --> 00:02:54,335
I intentionally decided to use this cute

59
00:02:54,375 --> 00:02:55,737
and silly aesthetic for the game,

60
00:02:56,037 --> 00:02:57,859
which I'll go into more detail later.

61
00:02:59,101 --> 00:03:00,961
So I just told you about the games I worked on.

62
00:03:01,021 --> 00:03:03,022
Here are some cute games that I like to play.

63
00:03:03,642 --> 00:03:06,143
So Animal Crossing is a game where you go fishing,

64
00:03:06,303 --> 00:03:08,163
catch bugs, and pay off your loans

65
00:03:08,203 --> 00:03:10,324
in order to acquire more debt from Tom Nook,

66
00:03:10,364 --> 00:03:12,364
the cute and adorable raccoon in the game.

67
00:03:13,304 --> 00:03:15,685
Neko Atsume is another cute game on my list.

68
00:03:16,385 --> 00:03:18,986
Leave out food for these cats and they'll give you sardines

69
00:03:19,066 --> 00:03:21,126
which you can use to buy additional food

70
00:03:21,166 --> 00:03:22,546
and toys for them later on.

71
00:03:22,626 --> 00:03:24,627
It's a game with pretty limited interaction,

72
00:03:24,987 --> 00:03:26,187
but I kept playing this one

73
00:03:26,227 --> 00:03:28,608
because I just wanted to collect all the cute cats.

74
00:03:29,668 --> 00:03:31,129
Threes is another one that I really like.

75
00:03:31,430 --> 00:03:33,791
It's this tiny puzzle game about matching numbers.

76
00:03:34,371 --> 00:03:36,993
And the design is really minimal but brilliant.

77
00:03:37,033 --> 00:03:39,455
And I think the cute faces on the tiles

78
00:03:39,635 --> 00:03:42,436
are just really charming and kind of add a lot

79
00:03:42,456 --> 00:03:44,378
to the look and feel of the entire game.

80
00:03:45,198 --> 00:03:49,879
P.O.Mori is a game where you want to stack as many baby chicks onto this plate of food

81
00:03:50,019 --> 00:03:51,920
and make sure they don't topple over.

82
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:55,021
You just want to try to make the biggest structure possible.

83
00:03:55,401 --> 00:04:00,443
And finally, Survive Mola Mola is this game that you can get on your phone.

84
00:04:00,843 --> 00:04:06,324
You're raising this sunfish and it's your job to make this Mola Mola grow as big as

85
00:04:06,384 --> 00:04:06,824
possible.

86
00:04:07,305 --> 00:04:12,326
But it's actually a game that's kind of dark because you have to kill your Mola Mola in

87
00:04:12,386 --> 00:04:13,686
order to make progress in the game.

88
00:04:14,207 --> 00:04:17,370
So you have to unlock every single death method,

89
00:04:17,470 --> 00:04:20,072
ranging from choking on every single type of food

90
00:04:20,393 --> 00:04:22,755
to dying on every adventure that your mola mola goes on.

91
00:04:23,635 --> 00:04:27,176
Anyway, so those are just some of the cute games I love to play, but the thing is, in

92
00:04:27,216 --> 00:04:30,258
general, we have a tendency to dismiss cuteness.

93
00:04:31,018 --> 00:04:34,080
We associate cuteness with being childish and immature.

94
00:04:34,580 --> 00:04:38,402
But today, I want to present a case for cuteness.

95
00:04:38,742 --> 00:04:45,605
So using my work as primary examples, I will show you how cuteness can attract, disarm,

96
00:04:46,406 --> 00:04:46,986
and engage.

97
00:04:48,006 --> 00:04:50,688
And you're basically making a mistake when you underestimate it.

98
00:04:51,692 --> 00:04:54,853
So my first point is cuteness grabs our attention.

99
00:04:55,773 --> 00:04:58,855
Many of the cute games I showed to you earlier are all

100
00:04:58,915 --> 00:04:59,775
really quite charming.

101
00:04:59,815 --> 00:05:01,996
And there's something about them that makes them feel

102
00:05:02,096 --> 00:05:03,437
really friendly and approachable.

103
00:05:04,057 --> 00:05:07,819
So I want to use Stellar Smooch as my main example to

104
00:05:07,859 --> 00:05:09,740
show you how cuteness is attention grabbing.

105
00:05:10,080 --> 00:05:11,240
So the way you play this game is.

106
00:05:15,209 --> 00:05:19,090
So you tap the screen to release and make the space probes smooch each other.

107
00:05:19,830 --> 00:05:25,453
And the game is short, it's roughly 24 levels, and there's this lovely poem which AP wrote

108
00:05:25,513 --> 00:05:27,313
that acts as part of the level select.

109
00:05:28,234 --> 00:05:32,135
So before the game looked like this, it looked like this.

110
00:05:32,495 --> 00:05:34,396
Actually it really looked like this.

111
00:05:34,776 --> 00:05:37,757
This is the prototype that AP made in a week with their Pixar art.

112
00:05:38,898 --> 00:05:41,619
But, so anyway, this is the version,

113
00:05:42,239 --> 00:05:44,681
the first iteration of art after I joined the project,

114
00:05:45,021 --> 00:05:48,243
and we kept this visual style in for a really long time.

115
00:05:48,863 --> 00:05:52,025
And even though there was nothing inherently wrong

116
00:05:52,045 --> 00:05:54,927
with the art, I felt like there was something missing

117
00:05:54,987 --> 00:05:55,407
about it.

118
00:05:55,767 --> 00:05:57,068
You know, the art didn't look terrible,

119
00:05:57,168 --> 00:06:00,089
but it also didn't feel really special.

120
00:06:00,410 --> 00:06:02,371
Maybe boring is the right word to describe it.

121
00:06:04,812 --> 00:06:09,513
And even though I swapped out the pixel art with this new visual style,

122
00:06:10,433 --> 00:06:13,194
it fundamentally didn't change the tone of the game.

123
00:06:13,814 --> 00:06:17,615
So the game still retained this very serious tone.

124
00:06:18,295 --> 00:06:19,495
And I mean, just look at the title.

125
00:06:19,515 --> 00:06:21,555
This is the original title of Stealth or Smooch.

126
00:06:21,675 --> 00:06:23,876
Dents in metal are just memories of an embrace,

127
00:06:24,176 --> 00:06:25,476
which is like a line from the poem.

128
00:06:25,916 --> 00:06:28,717
And the game just lacked any sort of humor.

129
00:06:29,657 --> 00:06:35,380
So when I was staring, so like I was staring at this particular screen for a really long time

130
00:06:35,980 --> 00:06:42,162
and just trying to figure out how to make the art better than it currently was, which is challenging

131
00:06:42,222 --> 00:06:46,744
because you know how do you take something that isn't really all that bad in the first place

132
00:06:46,904 --> 00:06:47,665
and make it better?

133
00:06:49,057 --> 00:06:51,738
And so I just drew faces over the planets.

134
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:54,340
And I know that sounds kind of like a silly answer,

135
00:06:54,460 --> 00:06:56,721
but once I added faces to them,

136
00:06:56,801 --> 00:06:59,822
there is something that felt right about the decision.

137
00:07:00,463 --> 00:07:02,764
By the way, I think it kind of relates

138
00:07:02,844 --> 00:07:05,045
to these images on the screen.

139
00:07:05,105 --> 00:07:08,126
So I don't know if anyone has heard of the term pareidolia,

140
00:07:08,506 --> 00:07:10,267
but examples of this phenomenon

141
00:07:10,367 --> 00:07:12,348
include perceiving a face within an,

142
00:07:13,329 --> 00:07:14,449
inanimate objects.

143
00:07:14,469 --> 00:07:16,571
So we see ourselves in everything,

144
00:07:16,611 --> 00:07:17,932
and this is just one of the ways

145
00:07:17,992 --> 00:07:19,833
that cuteness can grab our attention.

146
00:07:20,814 --> 00:07:22,174
So with that in mind,

147
00:07:22,194 --> 00:07:24,616
I basically started from scratch all over again.

148
00:07:24,636 --> 00:07:27,778
I began developing a new color palette for the game,

149
00:07:28,158 --> 00:07:30,340
and then I went on to add these little faces

150
00:07:30,420 --> 00:07:31,421
to the blobs of color,

151
00:07:31,501 --> 00:07:34,583
which would later become the faces of the planets.

152
00:07:35,163 --> 00:07:37,004
And I just kept iterating on it

153
00:07:37,104 --> 00:07:38,986
and trying out different expressions.

154
00:07:39,326 --> 00:07:41,867
I wanted to give the planets their own personalities.

155
00:07:42,669 --> 00:07:44,933
And finally, I ended up with these five planets.

156
00:07:45,795 --> 00:07:47,878
I experimented with adding detail to them,

157
00:07:47,998 --> 00:07:50,242
but decided against that decision in the end

158
00:07:50,302 --> 00:07:52,987
because I felt like embracing a more minimal look

159
00:07:53,107 --> 00:07:54,509
made the game more elegant.

160
00:07:55,582 --> 00:07:57,684
So I took away the excess detail,

161
00:07:57,804 --> 00:07:59,926
limited the color palette to only six colors,

162
00:08:00,066 --> 00:08:01,708
and ended up with these five planets

163
00:08:02,008 --> 00:08:03,530
that are the current ones in the game.

164
00:08:04,431 --> 00:08:06,052
And something I realized in hindsight

165
00:08:06,132 --> 00:08:08,275
is that by adding faces to the planets,

166
00:08:08,415 --> 00:08:10,677
I took these elements that were originally

167
00:08:10,737 --> 00:08:12,399
part of the environment of the game

168
00:08:12,719 --> 00:08:13,940
and made them into characters.

169
00:08:14,701 --> 00:08:17,285
By incorporating emotional states to the planets,

170
00:08:17,385 --> 00:08:19,168
the impact of winning or losing a level

171
00:08:19,328 --> 00:08:20,931
felt much more significant.

172
00:08:21,292 --> 00:08:23,535
And the game actually responded to your actions.

173
00:08:23,856 --> 00:08:26,820
It allowed for more expressive and interesting solutions

174
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:28,483
to other design problems we had.

175
00:08:29,643 --> 00:08:31,524
For example, this is just one of the problems

176
00:08:31,544 --> 00:08:33,026
that we were challenged with.

177
00:08:34,747 --> 00:08:37,650
Adding faces to the planets helped resolve this one issue

178
00:08:37,810 --> 00:08:40,672
where basically in the old version,

179
00:08:40,692 --> 00:08:44,876
this piece of ugly UI text would drop down

180
00:08:44,976 --> 00:08:47,198
from the top of the screen whenever you lost.

181
00:08:47,918 --> 00:08:50,840
and it would give you the option of trying the level again

182
00:08:50,860 --> 00:08:52,361
or going back to the main menu.

183
00:08:52,762 --> 00:08:55,664
And I really disliked this because I felt like

184
00:08:55,704 --> 00:08:58,726
it looked incredibly jarring and was like very clunky

185
00:08:59,687 --> 00:09:01,288
as a solution to this problem.

186
00:09:01,809 --> 00:09:06,172
So now when you lose, the planets will start crying

187
00:09:06,332 --> 00:09:07,833
and then like a restart button will fade

188
00:09:07,873 --> 00:09:08,914
into the corner of the screen.

189
00:09:08,934 --> 00:09:10,855
Oops.

190
00:09:11,636 --> 00:09:14,718
However, when you win, the planets, whoops, okay.

191
00:09:17,585 --> 00:09:20,086
Yeah, so when you win, the planets will smooch along

192
00:09:20,146 --> 00:09:23,107
and it's just like very clear to indicate

193
00:09:23,147 --> 00:09:24,708
whether or not you won or lost.

194
00:09:25,308 --> 00:09:27,349
And I just felt like this ultimately

195
00:09:27,409 --> 00:09:30,370
was just like a much more intuitive and elegant solution

196
00:09:30,430 --> 00:09:32,851
because it just reduced all these elements

197
00:09:32,891 --> 00:09:34,612
that previously had been on the screen

198
00:09:34,932 --> 00:09:37,853
and really focused on the parts of the game that mattered.

199
00:09:39,643 --> 00:09:42,805
Yeah, so, you know, the game shifted from being something

200
00:09:42,845 --> 00:09:45,726
completely serious and kind of boring and lacking any sort

201
00:09:45,746 --> 00:09:48,947
of humor to something cuter and more simple

202
00:09:49,087 --> 00:09:50,508
and with like a lot more character.

203
00:09:51,268 --> 00:09:55,050
And I just want to quickly talk about this process

204
00:09:55,550 --> 00:09:57,931
from Understanding Comics, which is this book

205
00:09:58,111 --> 00:09:59,152
by Scott McCloud.

206
00:09:59,772 --> 00:09:59,912
It's...

207
00:10:00,892 --> 00:10:04,114
Basically, I'd like to say the process that took place here

208
00:10:04,754 --> 00:10:07,616
is a form of amplification through simplification.

209
00:10:08,456 --> 00:10:13,499
And basically what it is, is like here's an illustration.

210
00:10:13,599 --> 00:10:15,019
So, you know, to your left,

211
00:10:15,380 --> 00:10:18,221
you see like a very realistic photograph of a man,

212
00:10:18,501 --> 00:10:20,963
but then like with each depiction,

213
00:10:21,383 --> 00:10:22,563
as you're moving towards the right,

214
00:10:22,703 --> 00:10:25,925
it gets more simple and the image becomes more abstract.

215
00:10:26,726 --> 00:10:28,827
And it's like, interesting to question,

216
00:10:28,847 --> 00:10:32,770
you know, this image of like two dots, a line and a circle,

217
00:10:33,751 --> 00:10:34,872
still resembles a face.

218
00:10:35,212 --> 00:10:38,795
And it's just like, as acceptable to us

219
00:10:39,515 --> 00:10:43,458
as the image of like the very realistically drawn man.

220
00:10:44,519 --> 00:10:49,962
So, when we abstract an image through this process of cartooning, you know, we're illuminating

221
00:10:50,002 --> 00:10:53,724
a lot of details and we're just focusing on the ones that really do matter.

222
00:10:54,705 --> 00:10:59,848
It's like basically taking the meaning that we want to get across and amplifying it.

223
00:11:01,501 --> 00:11:04,382
So in Cellar Smooch, by adding these faces to the planets

224
00:11:04,442 --> 00:11:06,682
and making them cuter, it just allowed me to focus

225
00:11:07,022 --> 00:11:09,303
my attention to the most important parts of the game.

226
00:11:09,803 --> 00:11:12,384
And as a result, it gave me the opportunity

227
00:11:12,424 --> 00:11:14,984
to just remove a lot of this unnecessary detail

228
00:11:15,084 --> 00:11:16,545
left over from the previous art style.

229
00:11:17,065 --> 00:11:19,265
So don't underestimate the importance

230
00:11:19,325 --> 00:11:21,966
of adding a face to something and making it cuter.

231
00:11:23,225 --> 00:11:27,066
So, however, the thing is, cuteness isn't always about

232
00:11:27,366 --> 00:11:29,027
being friendly and approachable.

233
00:11:29,627 --> 00:11:33,088
It can also act as a mask to hide darker motives.

234
00:11:33,588 --> 00:11:36,308
So in Animal Crossing, one of the first things you do

235
00:11:36,508 --> 00:11:38,369
is take a loan out from Tom Nook

236
00:11:38,449 --> 00:11:40,389
because you need to have a house in the game.

237
00:11:41,390 --> 00:11:43,450
And you need the loan to pay for it.

238
00:11:43,530 --> 00:11:45,851
So the game starts off by putting you into debt

239
00:11:45,911 --> 00:11:46,751
to this cute little guy.

240
00:11:48,022 --> 00:11:50,404
But the thing is, even after you pay off this loan,

241
00:11:50,524 --> 00:11:51,864
Tom Nook will always continue

242
00:11:51,884 --> 00:11:53,105
to take your money away from you,

243
00:11:53,405 --> 00:11:55,326
and he will always continue to put you into debt

244
00:11:55,386 --> 00:11:56,827
and acquire more and more property.

245
00:11:57,147 --> 00:12:00,429
He's kind of a little sinister in that sort of way,

246
00:12:00,469 --> 00:12:03,251
like underneath this cute, cuddly face lurks

247
00:12:03,451 --> 00:12:05,572
this more darker intent.

248
00:12:06,272 --> 00:12:08,694
And another example, maybe like a more clear example,

249
00:12:08,954 --> 00:12:12,575
is of cuteness acting as a mask for something

250
00:12:12,716 --> 00:12:15,177
far more sinister is Flowey from Undertale.

251
00:12:15,537 --> 00:12:17,658
You know, he's one of the first major characters

252
00:12:17,718 --> 00:12:18,999
that you meet in the game,

253
00:12:19,219 --> 00:12:22,561
and he appears to be super friendly and cute and charming.

254
00:12:23,241 --> 00:12:24,562
However, it's quickly revealed

255
00:12:24,622 --> 00:12:26,663
that Flowey is actually incredibly evil.

256
00:12:27,523 --> 00:12:30,685
He provides an introduction to the mechanics of encounters

257
00:12:30,725 --> 00:12:32,446
by sharing these friendliness pellets,

258
00:12:32,506 --> 00:12:34,387
which are actually harmful bullets.

259
00:12:35,220 --> 00:12:41,548
So, you know, Flowey's just another character that operates under this facade of friendliness.

260
00:12:41,668 --> 00:12:46,514
Whenever he drops the skies of cuteness, he often calls the protagonist an idiot.

261
00:12:47,850 --> 00:12:50,332
Which brings me to the main example at this point.

262
00:12:51,072 --> 00:12:54,574
In BeGlitched, cuteness acts as a mask

263
00:12:55,034 --> 00:12:57,735
and disarms people's initial expectations of the game,

264
00:12:58,096 --> 00:13:00,437
specifically in terms of the game's mechanics.

265
00:13:01,077 --> 00:13:03,298
Many people take one look at the game

266
00:13:03,819 --> 00:13:05,659
and underestimate the difficulty of it.

267
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,101
They think it might be easy PC to play it.

268
00:13:08,701 --> 00:13:10,902
Little do they know, it's actually a lot more harder

269
00:13:10,982 --> 00:13:13,203
than its pastel exterior might suggest.

270
00:13:14,996 --> 00:13:18,995
The cute aesthetic also masks the insecurity that the enemy hackers each possess.

271
00:13:20,273 --> 00:13:23,574
So each of these enemies have their own insecurities

272
00:13:23,654 --> 00:13:25,755
which cause them to lash out at the glitch witch.

273
00:13:26,015 --> 00:13:28,375
So examples of this include the squid being worried

274
00:13:28,415 --> 00:13:31,816
about his skills becoming irrelevant and becoming washed up.

275
00:13:32,736 --> 00:13:36,897
The ape feeling frustrated at his inability to copy

276
00:13:37,037 --> 00:13:39,237
or ape the techniques of the glitch witch.

277
00:13:39,977 --> 00:13:42,218
And the bear trying to compensate for his lack

278
00:13:42,258 --> 00:13:44,018
of hacking skills by purchasing

279
00:13:44,078 --> 00:13:45,658
the most powerful technology.

280
00:13:46,896 --> 00:13:50,997
However, cuteness does not necessarily have to hide dark and evil motives.

281
00:13:51,417 --> 00:13:54,678
It isn't always just about masking insecurity.

282
00:13:55,298 --> 00:13:56,998
Cuteness can be a form of rise

283
00:13:57,038 --> 00:13:59,499
and rebellion by subverting people's expectations.

284
00:13:59,939 --> 00:14:01,879
So the rise of cuteness in Japan emerged

285
00:14:01,959 --> 00:14:04,720
in the 1970s as part of this new writing style.

286
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:08,761
Many teenage girls began to write laterally with mechanical pencils.

287
00:14:09,081 --> 00:14:10,661
And these girls would write in big,

288
00:14:10,761 --> 00:14:13,762
rounded characters and add these little pictures to their writings,

289
00:14:13,802 --> 00:14:16,183
such as hearts, stars, emoticon faces.

290
00:14:17,003 --> 00:14:21,884
These pictures would be randomly inserted and make it really difficult to read. So in many of

291
00:14:21,924 --> 00:14:27,365
these cases, their teachers could no longer read their students' handwriting and the handwriting

292
00:14:27,385 --> 00:14:34,927
style was banned in many schools. However, during the 1980s, this new cute writing style was adopted

293
00:14:34,967 --> 00:14:40,528
by magazines and comics and even put onto packaging and advertising. This form of cute

294
00:14:40,568 --> 00:14:45,849
handwriting, which once was banned in schools, has kind of led to this rise of cuteness in Japanese

295
00:14:45,909 --> 00:14:46,230
culture.

296
00:14:47,190 --> 00:14:49,391
And speaking of cuteness in Japanese culture,

297
00:14:49,592 --> 00:14:52,433
is anyone familiar with the latest Sanrio character?

298
00:14:54,835 --> 00:14:56,356
So her name is Aggretsuko,

299
00:14:56,436 --> 00:14:58,938
and she's a 25 year old red panda

300
00:14:58,998 --> 00:15:02,220
working as an office associate in the accounting department

301
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:04,321
of a highly respected trading company.

302
00:15:04,902 --> 00:15:07,303
However, she's constantly taken advantage of

303
00:15:07,644 --> 00:15:09,985
and bothered by her boss and coworkers.

304
00:15:10,225 --> 00:15:12,287
She has to deal with getting much of the grunt work

305
00:15:12,327 --> 00:15:13,087
shoveled onto her.

306
00:15:14,377 --> 00:15:17,444
And there's this darker side to this seemingly cute character.

307
00:15:17,805 --> 00:15:23,136
So when Aggretsuko gets fed up of everything, she goes and screams death metal karaoke after work.

308
00:15:25,331 --> 00:15:27,632
So that was kind of my final example

309
00:15:27,712 --> 00:15:29,432
for cuteness acting as a mask

310
00:15:29,472 --> 00:15:31,493
for something much more darker and more sinister.

311
00:15:31,833 --> 00:15:32,814
Aggretsuko lets us,

312
00:15:33,254 --> 00:15:35,795
or has added dimension to her personality.

313
00:15:36,135 --> 00:15:38,696
You know, she's not only cute, but she's also tough.

314
00:15:39,236 --> 00:15:42,797
And it definitely lets us see how cuteness is flexible

315
00:15:42,897 --> 00:15:45,358
because it lets us look at how we can use

316
00:15:45,398 --> 00:15:47,999
this initial appearance of friendliness and charm

317
00:15:48,419 --> 00:15:50,299
to take people's expectations

318
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:52,720
and subvert them in regards

319
00:15:52,780 --> 00:15:54,421
to what's lying beneath the surface.

320
00:15:54,941 --> 00:16:00,970
Even with BeGlitched, it's a game that's telling you not to underestimate it based off its looks, and I think that's pretty cool.

321
00:16:02,492 --> 00:16:06,538
So my third point is, cuteness gives us room to experiment.

322
00:16:07,400 --> 00:16:09,543
So BeGlitched didn't always look this way.

323
00:16:10,809 --> 00:16:12,651
Even though it's a game about hacking,

324
00:16:12,891 --> 00:16:15,353
it doesn't really share the same aesthetic

325
00:16:15,513 --> 00:16:18,035
as most games that are traditionally cyberpunk.

326
00:16:18,616 --> 00:16:19,737
When you think of cyberpunk,

327
00:16:19,917 --> 00:16:22,139
maybe the first thing that pops into your mind

328
00:16:22,159 --> 00:16:27,043
are green, dark dystopias and ultra evil villains.

329
00:16:28,592 --> 00:16:31,275
which is what the original art of the game looked like.

330
00:16:31,696 --> 00:16:34,359
Yeah, so here's the original prototype that AP made.

331
00:16:34,379 --> 00:16:37,122
It was dark, green, and kind of serious.

332
00:16:37,703 --> 00:16:40,486
And that tone also reflected in the gameplay as well.

333
00:16:41,839 --> 00:16:44,541
When I joined the project, I kept this secret Tumblr,

334
00:16:44,641 --> 00:16:46,583
which I would use to later help develop

335
00:16:46,603 --> 00:16:47,964
my aesthetic for BeGlitched.

336
00:16:48,384 --> 00:16:52,648
I'd reblog images that I found attractive and cute,

337
00:16:52,948 --> 00:16:55,530
and it kind of embodied a certain sort of mood

338
00:16:55,570 --> 00:16:56,691
that I was going for.

339
00:16:57,071 --> 00:16:58,953
And at the same time, I was also really drawn

340
00:16:58,993 --> 00:17:01,895
to these pastel color palettes and this girly pink look.

341
00:17:06,612 --> 00:17:09,893
I also found these super cute versions of old computer UI.

342
00:17:10,354 --> 00:17:13,976
I loved how people created these really girly and cute interfaces.

343
00:17:14,416 --> 00:17:19,339
Something about the playfulness of this sort of imagery spoke to my inner 10-year-old who

344
00:17:19,619 --> 00:17:21,040
loves Hello Kitty and Tamagotchi.

345
00:17:21,400 --> 00:17:26,162
It wasn't just cute, it felt nostalgic in a way to me that green cyberpunk dystopias

346
00:17:26,222 --> 00:17:26,703
did not.

347
00:17:28,073 --> 00:17:31,835
However, this cute aesthetic doesn't really work for actual computer interfaces.

348
00:17:32,095 --> 00:17:33,595
Like think about click-clippy.

349
00:17:34,375 --> 00:17:39,017
It's kind of annoying and intrusive and gets in the way of what you're actually trying

350
00:17:39,057 --> 00:17:39,357
to do.

351
00:17:39,457 --> 00:17:45,079
So I think this cute aesthetic really only works for games because games are their own

352
00:17:45,639 --> 00:17:46,659
aesthetic universes.

353
00:17:46,999 --> 00:17:53,461
Having to compete in a space where everything else is at once is where you really want to

354
00:17:53,521 --> 00:17:55,222
assert this actual visual difference.

355
00:17:56,950 --> 00:17:59,091
So that's how I started iterating on the game.

356
00:17:59,692 --> 00:18:02,294
One of the first things I did was swap out all the colors

357
00:18:02,354 --> 00:18:03,735
and develop a new color palette.

358
00:18:03,995 --> 00:18:06,517
By the way, I didn't really know how to do pixel art

359
00:18:06,698 --> 00:18:07,898
before joining the project,

360
00:18:07,939 --> 00:18:10,220
so it didn't look very good at first.

361
00:18:10,981 --> 00:18:12,943
But I continued to iterate more and more,

362
00:18:13,003 --> 00:18:16,265
and I just redid the thing over and over again.

363
00:18:16,605 --> 00:18:19,107
And eventually the assets began to look better,

364
00:18:19,288 --> 00:18:22,610
and the visual style began to be more cohesive

365
00:18:22,650 --> 00:18:23,211
and clear to me.

366
00:18:26,198 --> 00:18:30,322
And yeah, it just like took a lot of trial and effort.

367
00:18:30,362 --> 00:18:32,344
I remember staring at the same colors

368
00:18:32,424 --> 00:18:35,547
and feeling like I was going crazy looking at this.

369
00:18:35,928 --> 00:18:37,810
Some days I wanted to rip my eyeballs out,

370
00:18:38,130 --> 00:18:40,853
but eventually after about a million iterations,

371
00:18:41,013 --> 00:18:44,056
I finally arrived with something that we both liked.

372
00:18:44,776 --> 00:18:46,578
And I'm really proud of the end result.

373
00:18:47,179 --> 00:18:49,982
Sure, I felt like this process took a lot of hard work

374
00:18:50,042 --> 00:18:54,086
and dedication and being critical about my own art,

375
00:18:54,166 --> 00:18:56,088
but being able to do something experimental

376
00:18:56,128 --> 00:18:58,611
in the first place and carry it out through completion

377
00:18:58,771 --> 00:19:01,935
is just like this incredibly invaluable experience to me.

378
00:19:03,741 --> 00:19:07,306
And in a way, being able to experiment like this,

379
00:19:07,727 --> 00:19:10,211
not being afraid to make mistakes and try out weird stuff

380
00:19:10,251 --> 00:19:11,833
has bled into my other work as well.

381
00:19:12,234 --> 00:19:14,858
So here are just some of the prototypes with my design

382
00:19:15,338 --> 00:19:17,321
that has been really driven visually.

383
00:19:19,016 --> 00:19:21,959
Morning Makeup Madness started out as something I doodled in Photoshop,

384
00:19:22,059 --> 00:19:25,782
and then I found out that incorporating this drawing mechanic

385
00:19:25,842 --> 00:19:30,066
that players could do creative stuff with

386
00:19:30,246 --> 00:19:34,570
is a really cool way to let players be expressive with their work.

387
00:19:34,910 --> 00:19:39,494
So after I made all these assets, I just brought them into Unity

388
00:19:39,654 --> 00:19:42,777
and then added some constraints with code,

389
00:19:43,077 --> 00:19:45,820
like a countdown and some colliders that would generate a score.

390
00:19:46,720 --> 00:19:49,744
Wobble Yoga is another visually driven game.

391
00:19:50,224 --> 00:19:53,027
So I wanted to learn about hinges that week,

392
00:19:53,347 --> 00:19:54,889
and joints, and unity.

393
00:19:54,969 --> 00:19:57,111
So I kind of made this little floppy toy,

394
00:19:57,531 --> 00:19:59,273
and then I added some more constraints,

395
00:19:59,593 --> 00:20:00,654
like very simple ones,

396
00:20:00,714 --> 00:20:02,696
like adding a meter to the bottom of the screen,

397
00:20:03,257 --> 00:20:05,179
and having poses that you needed to match.

398
00:20:09,047 --> 00:20:12,089
Here's a two-player game where one player is the octopus

399
00:20:12,309 --> 00:20:14,350
and the other player is the hand with the fork.

400
00:20:14,950 --> 00:20:17,691
And it later evolved into this prototype,

401
00:20:17,951 --> 00:20:19,712
which is a single-player game.

402
00:20:20,152 --> 00:20:22,433
Basically, the player controls my hand

403
00:20:22,553 --> 00:20:24,334
and depending on the food that you're holding,

404
00:20:24,654 --> 00:20:26,275
my head will react differently to it.

405
00:20:26,635 --> 00:20:32,458
So I'll chase unhealthy foods and avoid healthy foods.

406
00:20:36,621 --> 00:20:38,823
Yeah, so I'm not really the first person to do this.

407
00:20:38,843 --> 00:20:41,405
There are so many games out there that approach design

408
00:20:41,445 --> 00:20:43,607
with visuals first, or at least place an equal,

409
00:20:43,687 --> 00:20:46,069
if not more important, emphasis on the visual aesthetic.

410
00:20:46,369 --> 00:20:51,193
So Ho Ho Gum by Ricky Haggett and Richard Hogg is one example.

411
00:20:51,253 --> 00:20:52,774
Monument Valley by us too.

412
00:20:53,815 --> 00:20:56,037
Wrestling with Emotions by Team Laserbeam.

413
00:21:00,140 --> 00:21:01,421
Nog by Co-op Mode.

414
00:21:02,582 --> 00:21:04,984
And Anything Made by Sock Pub.

415
00:21:07,396 --> 00:21:13,144
So we mentioned how cuteness grabs our attention and how it can act as a mask to disarm our expectations

416
00:21:13,565 --> 00:21:15,508
and how it gives us room to experiment.

417
00:21:15,808 --> 00:21:18,252
Now I want to bring you to my final point.

418
00:21:18,553 --> 00:21:21,397
Cuteness connects us. It's inherently relatable.

419
00:21:23,179 --> 00:21:26,101
I want to quickly talk to you about Sanrio again.

